{
  "unmapped_findings": [
    "SAED analysis in Fig. 1 inset indicates Cu-rich phase has BCC structure, while subsequent HRTEM/IFFT analysis confirms FCC structure with (002) spacing of 0.182 nm, consistent with direct FCC precipitation in austenitic matrix",
    "Adding Cu increases austenite lattice parameter from 0.3687 nm (0Cu steel) to 0.3689 nm (3Cu steel), promoting κ-carbide precipitation",
    "Critical lattice parameter for intragranular κ-carbide precipitation is approximately 0.3670 nm",
    "Precipitation sequence: κ-carbide precipitates first during early aging stage, then promotes Cu-rich phase precipitation by enriching Cu concentration in surrounding matrix",
    "Cu atoms are excluded from κ-carbide precipitates and migrate to adjacent austenitic matrix, forming Cu-rich clusters upon reaching critical concentration",
    "Intragranular κ-carbide morphology: dots or bars; Cu-rich phase morphology: spherical or bars (irregular oval ~10 nm diameter, bars ~30 nm length)",
    "Lattice misfit between κ-carbide and Cu-rich phase is 3.4%, between κ-carbide and austenite is 2.3%, between Cu-rich phase and austenite is 1.0%",
    "Interfacial energy of κ-carbide with austenite (0.025 J/m²) is lower than Cu-rich phase with austenite (0.086 J/m²), explaining earlier precipitation of κ-carbide"
  ],
